                            <article class="post post-inner category-7" id="post-3035">               
                    <!-- Title area -->
                    <div class="rh_post_layout_default">
                        <div class="title_single_area">
                                                        <div class="breadcrumb" xmlns:v="http://rdf.data-vocabulary.org/#"><a href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/" rel="v:url" property="v:title">Home</a> &raquo; <span typeof="v:Breadcrumb"><a rel="v:url" property="v:title" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/category/101/">101 Guides</a></span> &raquo; <span class="current">Medical Alert System &#8211; Base Station Unit | 101 Guide</span></div><!-- .breadcrumbs --> 
                                                    
                            <h1>Medical Alert System &#8211; Base Station Unit | 101 Guide</h1>                                
                            <div class="meta post-meta">
                                				<span class="admin_meta">
			<a class="admin" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/author/medical_admin/">
								medical_admin			</a>
		</span>
	 		<span class="date_meta">February 10, 2016</span>	
						<span class="postview_meta">1737 </span>
			
			<span class="comm_count_meta"><a href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/base-unit/#respond" class="comm_meta" >no comments</a></span>
	 
                            </div>   
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                                        
                                                           

                    
                    <p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignleft" alt="" src="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/images/content/base-unit1.jpg" width="350" height="310" />The medical alert base unit is a hardware that is installed in the home of the person using the medical alert service, and <strong>the main purpose of the base unit is to establish the connection with the <a title="101 Guide | Call Centers" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/call-centers/">call center</a></strong> once the user presses the <a title="101 Guide | Alert Button Options (Pendent, Wristband, etc.)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/alert-button-options/">help button</a>. The base unit is essentially <strong>the heart of the system</strong>.</p>
<p>Base units have different designs, depending on the company that provides the service, but <strong>they all function in the similar way</strong>. They have a built-in speaker which allows users to communicate with the <a title="101 Guide | Call Centers" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/call-centers/">call center</a> agents when there is an emergency.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="" src="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/images/content/medical_system_demo.jpg" width="600" height="298" /></p>
<p>Once the user chooses a <a title="101 Guide | Medical Alert Companies (Services)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/companies-and-services/">medical alert company</a>, the necessary equipment which is needed to reach the <a title="101 Guide | Call Centers" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/call-centers/">call center</a> is shipped, and the base unit is an integral part of the package. <strong>The base unit comes with instructions on how to set it up and often the user installs the equipment alone</strong>, but there are companies that require additional payment for the installation of the unit, which is why you should check if the company charges installation fees, prior to ordering.</p>
<p><strong>The main difference between types of base units is in the <a href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/comparison/">type of connection</a>.</strong> Base units either use a <a title="101 Guide | Landline Connection Systems" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/landline-connection-systems/">landline</a> or <a title="101 Guide |  Cellular (Wireless) Connection Systems" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/cellular-wireless-connection-systems/">cellular network</a> for connection. The base unit can be for in-home only use or fully <a title="101 Guide | Mobile Systems (On-The-Go, GPS Tracking)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/mobile-systems/">mobile</a>. In case of a <a title="101 Guide | Mobile Systems (On-The-Go, GPS Tracking)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/mobile-systems/">mobile unit</a>, the base station is small and portable so that the user can easily carry it around. All <a title="101 Guide | Mobile Systems (On-The-Go, GPS Tracking)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/mobile-systems/">mobile base station units</a> use <a title="101 Guide |  Cellular (Wireless) Connection Systems" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/cellular-wireless-connection-systems/">cellular network for connection</a>.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong><span style="font-size: x-large;">How Does It Work?</span></strong></span></h2>
<p><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignright" alt="" src="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/images/content/base-unit2.jpg" width="320" height="350" /></strong>In-home base station <strong>usually looks like a phone answering machine</strong> and it has a built-in <strong>speakerphone on it for two-way communication</strong> in case of an emergency. The speakerphone is used for communication with the <a title="101 Guide | Call Centers" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/call-centers/">call center</a> because many of the systems do not offer <a title="101 Guide | 2-Way Communication feature" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/two-way-communication-feature/">two-way talking pendants</a>. This is why it is important to <strong>place the base station in a central location in the home.</strong> The base station unit frequently has a backup battery, which ensures that the connection with the <a title="101 Guide | Call Centers" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/call-centers/">help center</a> remains uninterrupted even during power failures. Base stations made <a title="101 Guide | Mobile Systems (On-The-Go, GPS Tracking)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/mobile-systems/">for mobile use</a> need to be charged regularly.</p>
<p><a title="101 Guide | Alert Button Options (Pendent, Wristband, etc.)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/alert-button-options/">Wearable help button</a> connects wirelessly to the base station, and the location of the base station and the size of the home will determine the <a title="101 Guide | Systems Optimal Range" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/optimal-range/">operational range</a>. The <a title="101 Guide | Systems Optimal Range" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/optimal-range/">range</a> of different base stations from different <a title="101 Guide | Medical Alert Companies (Services)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/companies-and-services/">companies</a> can considerably vary. <a title="101 Guide | Mobile Systems (On-The-Go, GPS Tracking)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/mobile-systems/">Mobile base stations</a> use the <a title="101 Guide |  Cellular (Wireless) Connection Systems" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/cellular-wireless-connection-systems/">cellular network</a> and they connect wirelessly to the <a title="101 Guide | Alert Button Options (Pendent, Wristband, etc.)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/alert-button-options/">help button</a>, this is exactly the same as with in-home systems.</p>
<p><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignleft" alt="" src="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/images/content/base-unit3.jpg" width="320" height="350" /></strong>The <a title="101 Guide | Mobile Systems (On-The-Go, GPS Tracking)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/mobile-systems/">mobile base station</a> will work anywhere where there is <a title="101 Guide |  Cellular (Wireless) Connection Systems" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/cellular-wireless-connection-systems/">cellular signal</a> coverage. <a title="101 Guide | Mobile Systems (On-The-Go, GPS Tracking)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/mobile-systems/">Mobile base station</a> is small and light and has a built-in speakerphone for two-way communication with the <a title="101 Guide | Call Centers" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/call-centers/">call center</a>. As soon as the user pushes the <a title="101 Guide | Alert Button Options (Pendent, Wristband, etc.)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/alert-button-options/">help button</a>, the base station calls the <a title="101 Guide | Call Centers" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/call-centers/">monitoring center</a> where the trained agent is awaiting to provide assistance. Some <a title="101 Guide | Mobile Systems (On-The-Go, GPS Tracking)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/mobile-systems/">mobile stations</a> also have a built-in GPS locating feature, this helps identify the location of the person in need &#8211; when on the go.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>When choosing a system, look through the <a href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/comparison/">specifications of the base station</a>.</strong> Check the following specifications: connection type (<a href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/comparison-landline/">landline</a> or <a href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/comparison-cellular/">cellular</a>), battery life, speakerphone range, <a title="101 Guide | Systems Optimal Range" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/optimal-range/">wireless button range</a>, design. <strong>Sometimes it is possible to find the same base station hardware sold by different companies</strong>, here the only difference is in the logo stamped on it and in <strong>the quality of the <a title="101 Guide | Medical Alert Companies (Services)" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/companies-and-services/">medical alert service</a> the company provides</strong>, otherwise the technical specifications should be the same.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Check our comparison tool on different base systems units »</span></p>
<ul>
<li><a title="" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/comparison-cellular/" target="_self">Compare medical alert systems with cellular connection &#8211; No Landline Needed »</a></li>
<li><a title="" href="https://medicalalertsystemreviews.net/comparison-landline/" target="_self">Compare medical alert systems with landline connection »</a></li>
</ul>

                </article>
